Ok, poison and alchemy are two different animals.<br>
<br>
The big difference between the two is the 'application'step.  On one hand, potions are right-click, self targeting,and charged (much like a pumice stone).  On the other, poisonsare right-click, add one spell proccess to primary piercing weaponand proccess remains active until zoned or consumed in an firstattack-hit, and single use.<br>
<br>
So the difference is inwhat they are applied to, how they are applied (i.e., spell versusa process), and whenther or not the original programming codewas implemented to allow for charges (in which poison was not).<br>
<br>
Confucious say, "If you can't go through the wallgo around it."<br>
<br>
Forget charges.<br>
<br>
Can the poisonapplication coding be re-written so that IF you successfullyapply your poison the actuial poison vial is not consumed; hence,you can use it again.  However, IF you fail your applicationthen the poison vial is destroyed.  This alleviates any writtencodes that utilize stacking or charges.  The code would stayessentially the same as it is now except the vial is not consumedafter a successful application.  <br>
<br>
Concerning the "experiencepays part of it", there could exist an initially base chance(base) of failure on any given apply.  I suggest base = 0.5 fora level 20 rogue.  As Apply Skill level increase a negitive modifier(mod = [(Apply Skill / 7.5)/ 100]) is subtracted from the basevalue. For example, a rogue with Apply Skill 225 would have a0.3 modifer.  The average life expectancy of a finished poisonvial would then be 1/(base-mod).  So our rogue with Apply Skillof 225 would, on average, get about 1/0.2, or five uses out ofa vial.  Of course he (or she) could have a bad day and failthe first one or have a good day and get more than four fiveapplications.  But overall would average five applications pervial.  [Note: the value 7.5 I chose above can be varied but asthat value approaches five the average number of uses in a finishedpoison approaches infinity.]<br>
<br>
So my solution is to forgetabout charges.  Just make it so if you DO NOT FAIL the applicationstep the finished poison remains.  If you DO FAIL the applicationstep the finished poison is destroyed.  Only a few codes needsto be changed: 1) the actual consumption of the poison afteraplication so if you succeed the icon remains in inventory, and2) the success rate of application for a given Apply Skill level[(base-mod)*100%].<br>
<br>
Can anyone give me some feedback?<br>
